In the equation, $\frac15+\frac{5}{x}=\frac{12}{x}+\frac{1}{12}$, what is the value of $x$?
inference:
$$\frac15+\frac{5}{x}=\frac{12}{x}+\frac{1}{12} $$ Solving for $x$, we have:
$$\frac15+\frac{5}{x}=\frac{12}{x}+\frac{1}{12} $$ $$\Rightarrow \frac{12}{x}+\frac{5}{x}-\frac{1}{5}-\frac{1}{12}=0 $$ $$\Rightarrow \frac{12+5}{x}-\frac{12-5}{60}=0 $$ $$\Rightarrow \frac{17}{x}-\frac{7}{60}=0 $$ $$\Rightarrow \frac{17}{x}=\frac{7}{60} $$ $$\Rightarrow x=\frac{17 \times 60}{7} $$ $$\Rightarrow x=150 $$ Final Answer: $\boxed{150}$. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth:
Subtract $\frac{5}{x}$ and $\frac{1}{12}$ from both sides of the equation to obtain \[
\frac{7}{60}=\frac{7}{x}.
\] By inspection, the solution of this equation is $x=\boxed{60}$.
